<DOC><DOCNO> AP890624-0100 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1513EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     06-24 0254</FIRST><SECOND>AM-South Korea,0260</SECOND><HEAD>Police Raid University Campus, Arrest Student Protesters</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Riot troopers backed by fire trucksraided a university campus before dawn Saturday and arrested 21students accused of organizing violent anti-government protests,police said.   Police said about 3,500 riot police searched two buildings atHanyang University in eastern Seoul for student leaders.   At least 21 students were arrested, but many more escaped beforepolice arrived, police said. Police said hundreds of firebombs andclubs were seized.   Radical students, a powerful minority on campuses, have used theHanyang campus as a stronghold of anti-government protests.   Also Saturday, in the southern provincial capital of Kwangju,news reports said about 400 radical students armed with firebombsand steel bars attacked prosecutors' offices, burning two cars andinjuring five policemen.   The attackers briefly occupied the compound of a three-storybuilding housing prosecutors' offices and fled after shatteringwindows of the building and 16 cars, the reports said.   Police arrested three students. One student was seriously injuredwhen he jumped off the top of the building, shouting slogansdenouncing the government, said Yonhap, the South Korean news agency.   Police have raided university campuses in recent weeks to arrestradical students leaders. About 500 dissidents and radicals havebeen arrested and sent to jail so far this year.   The dissidents are demanding the fall of the government ofPresident Roh Tae-woo and the withdrawal of the 43,000 U.S. troopsin South Korea. They say the American presence hampersreconciliation with communist North Korea.</TEXT></DOC>